There are two main reasons for that: focus and scale.=C2=A0
Focus. API-first companies focus on solving a very specific problem. Stripe=
 started with payments, and put all of their efforts into building the best=
 payments solution. Twilio started with messaging. Plaid does bank data, Al=
golia does search, Shippo does shipping, Checkr does background checks. Tha=
t focus means that everything the company does is oriented towards solving =
all of the problems related to that particular area.=C2=A0
Importantly, it means that everyone who works for those companies went ther=
e to solve those problems. Whereas an engineer at Uber who signed up to cha=
nge transportation would be pissed off if she were assigned to work on back=
ground checks, because it=E2=80=99s not the company=E2=80=99s core product,=
 an engineer at Checkr is stoked to work on background checks, because that=
=E2=80=99s what the company is all about!=C2=A0
Scale. API-first companies serve thousands or millions of customers, so the=
y=E2=80=99re able to justify small improvements that build up to an incredi=
ble product over time. Plaid can spend the effort to integrate with even ve=
ry small financial institutions, for example, since there will likely be th=
ousands of people who use that bank across all of the products that use Pla=
id.=C2=A0
API-first companies=E2=80=99 focus and scale give their software-building c=
ustomers best-in-class products that constantly improve at costs that scale=
 with their business. From the product side, they can be godsends. They=E2=
=80=99re also fascinating strategically in two ways: the competitive advant=
ages of the API-first companies themselves and the impact they have on thei=
r customers=E2=80=99 competitive advantages. Let=E2=80=99s start with their=
 customers.=C2=A0
Good Internet Strategy, Bad Internet Strategy
While I write more often about 7 Powers and The Outsiders, Richard Rumelt=
=E2=80=99s Good Strategy, Bad Strategy [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJ=
xFUMlugzAQ_Zr4BvKCjTn4kKpqTz31A5DBQ2IFbGQPRfTra5JDpdGMNNtbRotwi-kwa8xItgyp9=
84wxbWQTUecaRzTUhOf-ykBLNbPBtMGZN2G2Y8WfQzPC0q5JHcDorOD5ZNifHJSQMNU16i20c6p=
qWOcnDi93ZyHMIKBH0hHDEBmc0dc80VcL_yjxL7vtV3sbwz1GJfS-IzRVd-YTr5H9WZd9e6nCdL=
5pvqyiJByWXNrSVTQVmvFRUe84ZRTxmnLhFRM1Kz2isrOKmBwaehy43Xehox2fJxIJJkQcYjJh1=
sZP-52gfk5KIL7UpcteDx6CHaYwb28wJd7T2l4rGAC7HmGk9OrWQziXGrKVEsKmovFx_AP9AeZV=
ILa] is probably my favorite practical strategy handbook ever written.=C2=
=A0
Good strategy almost always looks simple and obvious and does not take a th=
ick deck of Powerpoint slides to explain. It does not pop out of some =E2=
=80=9Cstrategic management=E2=80=9D tool, matrix, chart, triangle, or fill-=
in-the-blanks scheme. Instead, a talented leader identifies the one or two =
critical issues in the situation =E2=80=94 and then focuses and concentrate=
s action and resources on them.
This is the beauty of API-first companies. They allow customers to focus on=
 the one or two things that differentiate their businesses, while plugging =
in best-in-class solutions everywhere else. Just as AWS and the cloud let e=
ntrepreneurs launch more cheaply, API-first businesses allow them to scale =
and professionalize with low upfront costs and managerial effort. As one pe=
rson in the space told me, =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s actually becoming crazy to=
 build your business in any way other than using all APIs except your point=
 of differentiation.=E2=80=9D
Jeff Lawson, the founder and CEO of leading API-first company, Twilio, migh=
t disagree with the premise of talking strategy at all. On the Bessemer Ven=
ture Partners Cloud Giants Podcast [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM=
1qwzAQhJ_GOhr9WLZ00KGlhEBzaVp6NbK0iUVsyZHkFOfpqyaHwsIuM-wO-xmd4RzippaQMloTx=
N5ZRVoqGG8ksqqxRHCBXOpPEWDWblI5roCWdZic0dkF_9jAmHI0qpbYgbFBCtkwbhh0QmjRsXKC=
SWI6if5yer1aB96AghvELXhAkxpzXlLFXiq6KxUW8HVaQnanrTZhLhIsLgULZaLfeyf1_b4Df9o=
3R_k5ve6vXxXbJVexN5-uN3J4H4-6bQy_RXK4puYDOUUxxYTijjDeElaT2rWYS90CgarB85nWaR=
1S1ubyl4ii8iEPITp_LvZl1DNMD6O83pc-r97lrQevhwnsk0p-cnw8mbcFlIefNEHOEJ9iQUUpF=
5i0HSppNhSi_j_oFylPhfo], he said:=C2=A0
I often say that strategy is a dirty word in business; it should be struck.=
 Any time you find yourself talking about strategy, you=E2=80=99re probably=
 off-course, actually. There=E2=80=99s only one business strategy: serve yo=
ur customers.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t think that Rumelt and Lawson would disagree, actually. Both=
 point at the same idea, that what people call =E2=80=9Cstrategy=E2=80=9D i=
s often a bunch of fancy words and falsely precise goals that obfuscate the=
 core purpose of the business: serving customers in a differentiated way. J=
udiciously using APIs where possible gives companies strategic clarity and =
the ability to solve their customers=E2=80=99 problems in a way that only t=
hey can.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s more! To learn what good strategy looks like on the interne=
t, why Shopify relies on Stripe, why API-first is such a good business mode=
l, and what I=E2=80=99m investing in=E2=80=A6
