itclr7PFllKPXJhBtbUYm7NpH-hPwzqdXo" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoratio=
n: underline;">Eric Vishria</a> describes it simply: people interact with s=
oftware through Graphical User Interfaces (GUIs), software interacts with s=
oftware through APIs.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">APIs handle an ever-increasing amou=
nt of things that get done in the world. Something that might have been a p=
en and paper process involving hundreds of people 50 years ago, and a dozen=
 people clicking a computer screen a decade ago, is probably software talki=
ng to other software via APIs today.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">There are three type=
s of APIs:&nbsp;</p><ol style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 3.75p=
x 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Internal APIs: </st=
rong>Used to do complex things more simply within a company.&nbsp;</p></li>=
<li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p=
 style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><=
strong>Public APIs:</strong> Typically used to open up datasets so others c=
an build on top of them.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px=
 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Vendor APIs:</strong> Give cu=
stomers the full superpowers of an entire company in a few lines of code.</=
p></li></ol><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Today, we&#8217;re focusing on Vendor APIs, also known=
 as third-party APIs. The companies who sell third-party APIs are called &#=
8220;API-first companies&#8221; (still with me?).&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"colo=
r: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Whereas=
